Our dinner here is best described as "under" -- undercooked, under-seasoned, and overall underwhelming.
My dude put it best: everything had a real "exhausted mom" quality to it, or just slightly above TV dinner quality.
Ordered: Shishito peppers - coated heavily in oil (not a good-tasting kind), under-seasoned, undercooked.
They were hardly grilled or fried; a couple were barely even warm.
I won't say no flavor, because there was a faint one, and it wasn't good.
Chicken pot pie - Isn't encrusted like most pot pies; has two cheesy biscuits on top.
And, oh yeah, they weren't cooked all the way through.
Neither were the potatoes, which were nearly raw.
One point in its favor: they used both white and dark meat.
The chicken, thankfully, was not undercooked, and the cream sauce was fairly tasty.
Pan seared trout - Not what you think it's going to be.
It's two thin pieces of fish, skin on, that seem to have been more pan fried.
Not super fresh.
Came with red cabbage and carrots, both pretty boring (the "sweet & sour" part was evidently false advertising for the cabbage), and white rice.
Had to squeeze the crap out of the lemon wedge all over the plate, as well as a fair amount of salt (I almost never salt my food at all, especially when I dine out, so that's another not-so-ringing endorsement).
Side of broccolini - No red pepper flakes to be found, in spite of the menu description.
Mostly tasted of lemon butter, but still not very delectable, though it was better than the shishito peppers, and not quite as undercooked.
Not the most offensive meal I've ever had, but for the price, nowhere near worth it.
I do not plan on coming back unless I hear they've majorly stepped up their game.
Other FYIs - no beers on tap, if you care about that sort of thing, though they do have a full bar (so our waiter said), the regular suspects of bottled beers, and some wines.
Despite the blah food, the waiters and hostesses are very nice.
Only reason it's not getting a 1 instead of a 2.

